      <div xml:id="NA136-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu ciṟaippuṟamākat talaivi tōḻikku uraittatu.
            2. ET: tōḻi talaivikku uraittatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is what SHE said to [her] confidante while [HE] was behind the fence.
            2. ET: It is also what the confidante said to HER.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA136">
        <lg type="edition">
<l rend="indent4">            kēṭṭiciṉ vāḻi tōḻiyi toṉṟu</l>
<l>            tiruntukō lelvaḷai vēṇṭiyā ṉaḻavu</l>
<l>            marumpiṇi yuṟunarkku vēṭṭatu koṭāatu</l>
<l>            maruntāyntu koṭutta vaṟavōṉ pōla</l>
<l>            veṉṉai vāḻiya palavē paṉṉiya</l>
<l>            malaikeḻu nāṭaṉoṭu nammiṭaic ciṟiya </l>
<l>            talaippiri vuṇmai yaṟivāṉ pōla</l>
<l>            nīppa nīṅkātu variṉvarai yamaintu</l>
<l>            tōṭpaḻi maṟaikku mutavip</l>
<l>            pōkkil polantoṭi ceṟīi yōṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>{Listen, oh friend, this [is] one thing:}</l>
<l>May my lord live for many [days],</l>
<l rend="indent">[he who was] like a doctor that selected [and] gave a remedy,</l>
<l rend="indent">not giving the thing wanted, to one who has a difficult disease<note place="foot">Here we have a passage where <term xml:lang="ta">piṇi</term> is unequivocally used in the extended meaning of "disease".</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when I cried wanting bright bangles in a perfect row,</l>
<l>– he who tightened a golden bracelet that doesn't move [on my arm],</l>
<l rend="indent2">a help that hides the blame of [my] shoulder, fitting exactly,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when he comes incessantly<note place="foot">I suggest to take <term xml:lang="ta">nīṅkātu</term> here in an adverbial sense, the point being a play on <term xml:lang="ta">nīṅku</term>, in the sense that he does not leave off coming only in order to leave again.</note>, in order to leave [again],</l>
<l rend="indent">as if he knew of the existence of the small(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ciṟiya</term> presumably has to be taken as an attribute (marked for plural) to <term xml:lang="ta">talaipirivu</term> (= <term xml:lang="ta">pirivu</term>?): many small separations, since in between HE is coming again to see HER.</note> separations</l>
<l rend="indent2">on our part from the man from a land of close-set(?)<note place="foot">Actually the verb <term xml:lang="ta">paṉṉu</term> (here the pey. p.a. <term xml:lang="ta">paṉṉiya</term>) seems to be a hapax in Caṅkam poetry, and what it may mean here is anybody’s guess. The variant <term xml:lang="ta">maṉṉiya</term> taken up by ET might be an argument for the choice of semantic nuance made above.</note> mountains.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
